definition.value: A primary amino compound that is the 5-hydroxy derivative of tryptamine.
A straight-chain alkane with 12 carbon atoms. It has been isolated from the essential oils of various plants including Zingiber officinale (ginger).

A C20 striaght-chain saturated fatty acid which forms a minor constituent of peanut (L. arachis) and corn oils. Used as an organic thin film in the production of liquid crystals for a wide variety of technical applications.

A C18 straight-chain saturated fatty acid component of many animal and vegetable lipids. As well as in the diet, it is used in hardening soaps, softening plastics and in making cosmetics, candles and  plastics.
The 5alpha-stereoisomer of androstane.
The conjugate base of a fatty acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group of the corresponding fatty acid.
Any glycerophosphoinositol having one phosphatidyl group esterified to one of the hydroxy groups of inositol.
A straight-chain, fourteen-carbon, long-chain saturated fatty acid mostly found in milk fat.
A phenylalanine derivative comprising L-phenylalanine having [bis(2-chloroethyl)amino group at the 4-position on the phenyl ring.
A molecule composed of a glycosphingolipid (ceramide and oligosaccharide) with one or more sialic acids linked on the sugar chain.
A bisphosphoglyceric acid that is glyceric acid carrying two phospho substituents at positions 2 and 3.
The R-enantiomer of adrenaline. It is a hormone secreted by the adrenal glands resulting in the 'fight-or-flight' response.
An onium cation obtained by protonation of ammonia.
Any sugar having one or more alcoholic hydroxy groups replaced by substituted or unsubstituted amino groups.
A carboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of any dicarboxylic acid.
An alpha-amino acid that is glycine in which the alpha-is substituted by a 3-guanidinopropyl group.
A member of the class of bilanes that is a colourless product formed in the intestine by the reduction of bilirubin.
The conjugate base formed when the carboxy group of a carboxylic acid is deprotonated.
The L-enantiomer of ascorbic acid and conjugate acid of L-ascorbate.
A monoatomic monocation obtained from sodium.
A monoatomic monocation obtained from potassium.
An organosulfur compound in which a thiol group, -SH, is attached to a carbon atom of any aliphatic or aromatic moiety.
A divalent inorganic anion resulting from the removal of two protons from ammonia.
A carboxamide derived from a monocarboxylic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid amide derived from a fatty acid.
A C4-dicarboxylate that is the E-isomer of but-2-enedioate(2-)
A prephenate(2-) obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of (1s,4s)-prephenic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
